The previous assumption must be corrected.

The difference between the sexes, is determined in the different trills at each call end and not by the frequency level.

The clear allocation I made 2015 by comparing the calls of genetically determined swifts.

A distinction between female swifts  and male swifts  in flight, becomes visible by spektrogramm of the calls.
To distinguish between males and females when making a solo call is almost impossible for people to hear.
The Doppler effect also changes the frequency and makes the assessment more difficult.

The differences are not visible in the XENO-CANTO graphic.
Only the transfer to AudaCity  makes the subtleties visible of the calls in the spectrum graph.

A flock feeding over the river, together with Swifts and House martins.

The sound of these Common Swifts (same as XC327489) were altered by implementing a 87% deceleration. This resulted in an amazing recording in wich you can hear the complexity of their calls. A must hear! A very instructive moment perhaps?

Check out sounds starting at 1:10, 3:14, 4:32, 5:28  and 6:50
The sound at 1:49 is of a bird flying into the guttering on my house and entering its nest-site, to roost for the evening.
Mainly low-intensity calls from high-flying flock of c. 30 birds, with occasional, low, high-speed flights around rooftops.

Recording during last c. 20 minutes of light after a generally warm day (c. 26oC), with a flock of c. 30 swifts very high in the sky (probably > 500 m above ground) calling almost continuously, especially in the second half of the cut. Also much lower birds, c. 10 in total, chasing each other regularly throughout the first two-thirds of the recording (sometimes only their wingbeats are audible), including at least two of the four individuals nesting in my house, both of which entered their nest (the same one) separately during the middle portion of the cut.
Largely calls from flock high above ground, with occasional screams from small flocks of birds chasing each other at rooftop level.

Many birds seem to have finished breeding now, but are much more evident around the colony in the mid to late morning than earlier in the season; total of c. 20 different birds probably can be heard in this recording, mostly giving low-intensity and infrequent calls, but occasionally groups of up to eight individuals are heard chasing each other low over my house.

A c. 2-week-old nestling Apus apus that had fallen from its nest and is being hand-reared. Generally lower-intensity calls than in XC325790, as the bird is not being fed at this stage, but these and similar calls are maintained almost constantly. Sound of a door banging in another office at 0:33. Wing-flapping by the swift at 1:09. Recorded using a mobile phone.

A c. 2-week-old nestling Apus apus that had fallen from its nest and is being hand-reared. The background noises that start at 0:10 are the sounds of Pascal opening and closing the box in which he keeps house crickets to feed the bird. Recorded using a mobile phone.

Calls from a few close birds; extracting from recording of Western Jackdaw.

Bevor ich Übersetzungsfehler mache, …;-) 

Letztes  Jahr (2013) wartete ein Mauersegler fast 14 Tage auf die  Ankunft des zweiten Mauerseglers,
vermutlich auf das Weibchen.  
Das der/die NEUE ankam war nicht zu verkennen und ich  startete sofort ein Video. 
Fast eine Stunde dauerte es bis auch der zweite Segler in den Kasten zurückkam. 
Dann begann ein Paarungsritual das zum Teil sehr heftig und laut durchgeführt wurde.
Diese Stimmen waren auch für das Mikrofon zu laut und sind fast unbrauchbar.
Aber zum Ende hörte ich leise Stimmen, die von den Seglern nicht oft zu hören sind.
Um einige Pausen gekürzt sind diese Stimmen in dem File zusammengefasst. 
Die raschelnden Geräusche entstanden durch die Bewegung  der Segler.

recordings.rmk: At this stage, there are still five or six active nests in the colony, but the adults are almost entirely silent, scarcely ever calling in flight, and never giving loud screams and their feeding behaviour is mainly alone and very intent, with little interaction between them. Only two or three adults will ever feed in the same general airspace together, and then only briefly. Most feeding also appears to be well away from the colony. This recording (same bird/s as in XC383113) is of a young, presumably close-to-fledging nestling just after one of its parents had arrived at the nest approximately 10 minutes before dusk; the adult responded with similar but probably quieter calls. The calling continued until after darkness had fallen.

En las zonas bajas de Andalucía el vencejo pálido, Apus Pallidus, es la especie más usual aunque también se puede encontrar el común, pero en los pueblos de la sierra de Huelva las colonias casi son exclusivamente de esta última especie.

Screams from a flock of ~80 birds over high mountain ridge thought to be this species and not A. barbatus. Normally silent on winter grounds, these birds were probably very recent arrivals. Subspecies uncertain as views poor and both nominate and pekinensis occur.

Gritos de los integrantes de una colonia de cría volando alrededor del lugar donde emplazan sus nidos, la iglesia del pueblo. En el sur de la península ibérica Apus Apus habita principalmente en zonas montanas y también en las zonas bajas, en estos últimos lugares en bastante menor número que Apus Pallidus y confundiéndose entre éstos por la similitud de sus vocalizaciones y de su aspecto físico. La voz de Apus Apus es más aguda y su color más oscuro con la mancha de su garganta menos patente. Éste es un pueblo ubicado en la sierra de Huelva, por lo que mayormente los vencejos que en él habitan son Apus Apus.
